WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.700
So are we closer to curing CLL? I think so. These are my disclosures.

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:11.780
So we'll start with a brief history lesson. I had to fish this slide out, no pun intended.

00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:17.420
This is a cohort of patients enrolled in the 90s with CLL who are being observed for their

00:00:17.420 --> 00:00:22.260
survival outcomes. And you can see here, patients with favorable risk cytogenetics or molecular

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:27.740
profile have the best outcomes. But for those high-risk patients like deletion 17P, overall

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:33.220
survival is less than three years. So what were our tools back then, and how far have we come?

00:00:34.520 --> 00:00:39.200
So bear with me with this slide. This is my first attempt at using AI to create one. I think it did

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:44.780
an okay job. Back in the 90s and early 2000s, our tools were traditional chemotherapy,

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:51.040
fludarabine, chlorambucil, rituximab, bendamestine, ofatumab were the big wins back then.

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:56.380
In the 2010s, that's when we moved into the targeted era, right? We have our BTK inhibitor

00:00:56.380 --> 00:00:57.720
ibrutinib, PI3A1, and we have our B2K inhibitor ibrutinib. So we have our B2K inhibitor ibrutinib,

00:00:57.720 --> 00:00:57.720
B2K inhibitor ibrutinib, PI3A1, and B2K inhibitor ibrutinib. So we have our B2K inhibitor ibrutinib,

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:02.020
B2K inhibitor ibrutinib, B2K inhibitor ibrutinib, B2K inhibitor ibrutinib, and of course our BCL2

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:07.720
inhibitor venetoclax. And we have had success with this. So this is long-term follow-up from

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:13.200
Resonate 2, looking at ibrutinib in treatment-naive patients with CLL. The median progression-free

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:18.740
survival with ibrutinib was almost nine years, and this held up even for those high-risk patients

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:26.520
with mutated TP53, unmutated IGHV, deletion 11q. And at nine years, our median overall survival

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:27.720
had still not been reduced. So we have our B2K inhibitor ibrutinib, B2K inhibitor ibrutinib,

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:34.200
and this is true even in those high-risk patients. We see similar success with the

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:40.480
second-generation B2K inhibitors. Acalabrutinib's data in Elevate TN at six years, median PFS still

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:46.700
has not been reached. From Sequoia, we have data with Xanabrutinib in deletion 17q patients,

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:53.620
regardless of your IGHV mutation status. At five years, more than 70% of patients are progression

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:57.700
free. With venetoclax, we have learned now that

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:03.820
fixed-duration therapy is feasible, right? This is data with venobin from CLL14. These are time-to-next

00:02:03.820 --> 00:02:08.320
treatment curves. So for our favorable-risk patients, they can go several years without

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:13.020
needing another line of therapy. Even our higher-risk patients can benefit, albeit for

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:19.320
shorter durations. And now we're in the next frontier with oral doublets. With Captivate,

00:02:19.400 --> 00:02:23.460
patients got fixed duration of ibrutinib and venetoclax. In five and a half years,

00:02:23.460 --> 00:02:27.500
we still haven't reached our median PFS. For high-risk patients,

00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:32.460
a little bit lower, but that's a great concept. And of course, we have Amplify with the calibrutinib

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:37.520
and venetoclax. This combination has also recently been FDA-approved for treatment-naive patients

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:44.980
without delt 17p. We now have more promising sequencing data. From the core registry,

00:02:45.460 --> 00:02:51.240
we know that venetoclax is a very effective option after covalent PTK inhibitors. We have data from

00:02:51.240 --> 00:02:57.580
Captivate showing retreatment with IV after IV is an effective option. At the Summer Congress,

00:02:57.660 --> 00:03:02.520
last year, we saw preliminary data from RevengeG showing venobin as a very reasonable

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:08.440
or looks promising after venobin. And of course, we have data from HOVON 159 showing that you can

00:03:08.440 --> 00:03:16.040
use AV after ven plus CD20. Despite these incredible advances, there's still an unmet

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:22.860
need that remains. For patients who are refractory to covalent PTK inhibitor and venetoclax, their

00:03:22.860 --> 00:03:27.100
progression-free survival to the next line of therapy has traditionally been quite poor. So

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:27.640
this is an area where we're going to have to look at how we're going to be able to

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:32.520
focus on this area that we really need to focus. And luckily, we have made success there.

00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:38.260
So over the next few days, you're going to hear more about the second-generation covalent PTK

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:43.080
inhibitors, acalabrutinib and venetoclax. You're going to hear about the covalent PTK

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.140
ipertabrutinib. I'll be talking about that tomorrow. You'll be hearing more about CAR-T

00:03:47.140 --> 00:03:53.840
cell therapy, which now has an FDA approval for CLL, and a totally new class of drugs known as

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:55.100
BTK degraders.
